description: Borrowed from Latin extricatus, past participle of extric≈ç.

verbs.description: extricate (third-person singular simple present extricates, present participle extricating, simple past and past participle extricated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To free, disengage, loosen, or untangle.
examples: I finally managed to extricate myself from the tight jacket.
The firefighters had to use the jaws of life to extricate Monica from the car wreck.

entries.meaning: (rare) To free from intricacies or perplexity
examples: Your argumentation ... is invelloped with certain intricacies, that are not easie to be extricated.
